munity.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/56b4756feb3b30c1b570201c0e2216c4a05a6e1a.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f1036cc8393b3ef40451d45e9091fb9213bf92ce.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/754a0317c68293f33bf12e18ebae4de2b08f81b7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5954894f377de2935fd0505a2dfa91e1229e52cd.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/05bfab6050393e6c96f3a1bf8e5a5fcb099320ba.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0160df6b10af9f47f73802569b3923b422f58dc3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ff0fc320b13a75505e6aa3cb9cccd5f49de22167.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8f875f53214515cd7d91639a705e7a3967643aa7.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":".com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5954894f377de2935fd0505a2dfa91e1229e52cd.png]\nDescription: The image displays the \u0022Model Browser\u0022 interface within a software application labeled \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The visible hierarchy includes sections such as \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 and \u0022Lookups.\u0022 Under the \u0022Data\u0022 category, subcategories include \u0022Constants,\u0022 \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 \u0022Database Data Types,\u0022 \u0022Entities,\u0022 and \u0022Functions.\u0022 Highlighted within \u0022Lookups\u0022 is \u0022Data Service Lookup,\u0022 with a dropdown context menu showing options: \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New\u0022 (F12), \u0022Actions,\u0022 \u0022Convert To,\u0022 and \u0022Move To Package.\u0022 The purpose appears to facilitate managing and creating new data service lookups within the application.\n\n\n  \n \n Fill in the following fields: \n \n \n \n  Name : Use the default naming convention  EntityName_FieldName_FilterName  \n \n \n  ListDataStructure : Select the Data Structure you previously created. \n \n \n  ListDisplayMember : Insert the name of the field you want to display in your drop-down menu. \n \n \n  ListValueMember : Insert the name of the field you want to use as a reference (usually the ID). \n \n \n  ValueDataStructure : Select the Data Structure you previously created. \n \n \n  ValueDisplayMember : Insert the name of the field you want to display in the form after selecting it from the drop-down menu. \n \n \n  ValueMethod : Select GetId. \n \n \n  ValueValueMember : Insert the name of the field you want to use as a reference (usually the ID). \n \n \n After filling in these fields, the form may look like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/05bfab6050393e6c96f3a1bf8e5a5fcb099320ba.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface for a \u0022Data Service Lookup\u0022 configuration titled \u0022Priority_Name_GetId.\u0022 The UI contains several sections labeled as \u0022(Info),\u0022 \u0022Filter,\u0022 \u0022List,\u0022 \u0022Misc,\u0022 and \u0022Value.\u0022 Under \u0022(Info),\u0022 it lists details like \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable\u0022 (set to False), and \u0022Name\u0022 with its value. The \u0022Filter\u0022 section includes parameters such as \u0022FeatureFilterMember\u0022 and \u0022RoleFilterMember.\u0022 The \u0022List\u0022 section specifies attributes like \u0022AlwaysAllowReturnToForm\u0022 (False), \u0022IsFilteredServerside\u0022 (False), and \u0022ListDisplayMember\u0022 with a value of \u0022Name.\u0022 Under \u0022Misc,\u0022 the parameters \u0022ValueColumn\u0022 and \u0022ValueDisplayColumn\u0022 are shown, both associated with \u0022Id\u0022 and \u0022Name,\u0022 respectively. The \u0022Value\u0022 subsection outlines the \u0022ValueDataStructure\u0022 and \u0022ValueMethod,\u0022 which is \u0022Get Id.\u0022 Overall, this interface seems to facilitate the configuration of a data service lookup related to priority identification.\n\n\n  \n Save it and your Lookup is ready to be used. \n   Lookup with Entity and Field \n Now that you know how to create a Lookup for an existing entity and field, you can learn a shortcut using an action that creates everything for you in one wizard: \n \n Database Entity \n Database Field \n Data Service Lookup \n \n To use this shortcut, right-click on any existing entity and choose  Actions  /  Create Lookup Field (incl. entity) : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0160df6b10af9f47f73802569b3923b422f58dc3.png]\nDescription: The image appears to show a user interface for a software application, likely related to database or application development. The left pane, labeled \u0022Entities,\u0022 contains a tree structure with nodes for \u0022Origam General Interfaces,\u201D \u201CDimensions,\u201D and \u0022myapplication,\u0022 among others. A dropdown menu is prominently displayed, featuring options including \u0022Create Lookup...,\u0022 \u0022Create Lookup Field (incl. entity)...,\u0022 \u0022Create Screen...,\u0022 and \u0022Actions,\u0022 with highlighted selections for various functions like \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 and \u0022Execute.\u0022 This interface suggests functionality for managing entities and generating related configurations within a software environment.\n\n\n  \n A wizard will open: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ff0fc320b13a75505e6aa3cb9cccd5f49de22167.png]\nDescription: The image displays a dialog titled \u0022Create Field With Lookup Entity.\u0022 It outlines a process with the subheading \u0022What will happen...\u0022 The primary instruction indicates that the wizard will create the following elements necessary for the function of the menu: \u0022Database Entity,\u0022 \u0022Database Field,\u0022 and \u0022Data Service Lookup,\u0022 each accompanied by corresponding icons. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":